    <!-- Myths & FAQ -->
    <section class="section faq">
        <div class="container">
            <h2 class="section-title">Busting Myths & Common Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(0)">
                        <span>Myth: Only women with family history get breast cancer</span>
                        <svg class="faq-icon" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
                            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z"/>
                        </svg>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <strong>Fact:</strong> 80% of women diagnosed with breast cancer have no family history. While family history increases risk, anyone can develop breast cancer.
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(1)">
                        <span>Myth: Cervical cancer only affects older women</span>
                        <svg class="faq-icon" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
                            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z"/>
                        </svg>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <strong>Fact:</strong> Cervical cancer can occur at any age after puberty. Regular screening from age 21 is crucial for early detection.
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(2)">
                        <span>Myth: Small breasts have lower cancer risk</span>
                        <svg class="faq-icon" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
                            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z"/>
                        </svg>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <strong>Fact:</strong> Breast size has no correlation with cancer risk. All women, regardless of breast size, should perform regular self-exams.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFAQ(3)">
                        <span>Myth: Birth control pills cause cervical cancer</span>
                        <svg class="faq-icon" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
                            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.293 7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0L10 10.586l3.293-3.293a1 1 0 111.414 1.414l-4 4a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 010-1.414z"/>
                        </svg>
                    </button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <strong>Fact:</strong> There's a slight increase in cervical cancer risk with long-term oral contraceptive use, but the benefits usually outweigh the risks. Regular screening is key.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

